es -- tReligion, Conflict and Moderation -- tScience and the Unearned Virtues of the ‘Really Religious People’: Exploring the Association between Perceived Religiosity and Science Rejection among Students in the Midwestern United States -- tDiscourses on Science and Islam: A View from Britain -- tConclusion: Future Directions in the Sociological Study of Science and Belief -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe relationship between science and belief has been a prominent subject of public debate for many years, one that has relevance to everything from science communication, health and education to immigration and national values. Yet, sociological analysis of these subjects remains surprisingly scarce. This wide-ranging book critically reviews the ways in which religious and non-religious belief systems interact with scientific theories and practices. Contributors explore how, for some secularists, ‘science’ forms an important part of social identity. Others examine how many contemporary religious movements justify their beliefs by making a claim upon science. Moving beyond the traditional focus on the United States, the book shows how debates about science and belief are firmly embedded in political conflict, class, community and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aBelief and doubt. 0aReligion and science. 0aReligion and sociology. 0aSciencexSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh1 aCarlisle, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCatto, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCatto, Rebecca, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavie, Grace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular